.9058V10.6071C10.8107 9.18295 11.2173 7.78848 11.9819 6.58696C12.7466 5.38544 13.8377 4.42659 15.1275 3.82264C16.4173 3.21869 17.8524 2.99464 19.2649 3.1767C20.6775 3.35876 22.0089 3.93941 23.1034 4.85067C23.0427 4.88379 22.937 4.94215 22.8668 4.98473L14.9024 9.58517C14.7025 9.69878 14.5366 9.86356 14.4215 10.0626C14.3065 10.2616 14.2466 10.4877 14.2479 10.7175L14.2424 21.9419ZM16.071 17.9991L20.4018 15.4978L24.7325 17.9975V22.9985L20.4018 25.4983L16.071 22.9985V17.9991Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>The concept of the Markov blanket is used to formalize the idea of conditional independence in a system, which is necessary for the system to exist as an integrated whole with well-defined boundaries. The Markov blanket is a set of states that shield a system from its external environment, and it is made up of sensory and active states. Internal states are insulated by the blanket from external states, which can only indirectly influence internal states through their impact on sensory states. Similarly, internal states can only indirectly affect external states through their impact on active states. This insulation creates the appearance that the organism and its environment are inferring each other's states and statistical properties, which manifests as action, perception, and learning. Overall, the Markov blanket is a valuable tool for formalizing the notion of conditional independence and understanding how it applies to complex systems such as the mind and multiscale cognitive systems.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" 